ðŸ”¹ What is dnsrecon?

      dnsrecon is a Python-based DNS reconnaissance and enumeration script used to gather DNS-related information about a domain: standard records (A, MX, NS, SOA, TXT, etc.), zone transfers, wildcard checks, DNSSEC info, subdomain brute-forcing, reverse lookups, and more. Itâ€™s included in Kali and widely used by pen-testers and red-teamers.

Key capabilities:

    -Standard DNS record enumeration (A, AAAA, MX, NS, SOA, TXT, SPF)

    -Zone transfer (AXFR) checks against authoritative name servers

    -Subdomain brute-force using a wordlist

    -PTR (reverse) sweeps for an IP range or CIDR

    -DNSSEC and wildcard detection

    -Export results to machine-readable formats (XML/CSV/JSON)

ðŸ”¹Why use dnsrecon?

    -All-in-one DNS tool: one script combines many useful DNS reconnaissance tasks.

    -Fast reconnaissance: good for the information-gathering phase in pentests and red-team engagements.

    -Exportable output: XML/CSV/JSON support makes it easy to save, report, or chain into other tools.

    -Flexible: point it at custom resolvers, use specific nameservers, or supply your own dictionaries.

ðŸ”¹Common usage patterns

    Use dnsrecon -h to view flags available on your local version. Below are practical examples and the most commonly used flags.

Basic command syntax:

    dnsrecon -d <domain> [options]

ðŸ”¹Common flags

    -d <domain> â€” Target domain.

    -t <type> â€” Type of enumeration. Common types:

    std â€” Standard records (default).

    brt â€” Brute force subdomains with a dictionary.

    axfr or using -a â€” Zone transfer checks.

    rev â€” Reverse PTR sweep on an IP range/CIDR.

    -D <dictionary> â€” Wordlist for brute forcing subdomains.

    -n <nameserver> â€” Use a specific DNS server for queries.

    -r <range> â€” Reverse lookup on an IP range or CIDR.

    --xml <file> â€” Save output as XML. (Other versions may support JSON/CSV.)

Examples

1.Standard enumeration

        dnsrecon -d example.com

2.Subdomain brute-force using a wordlist

        dnsrecon -d example.com -D /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Discovery/DNS/subdomains-top1million-5000.txt -t brt

3.Try zone transfers (AXFR) and standard checks

        dnsrecon -d example.com -a

4.Reverse PTR sweep on a CIDR

        dnsrecon -r 198.51.100.0/24

Save results to XML

        dnsrecon -d example.com -D wordlist.txt -t brt --xml results.xml
